Okay, a couple things to add which I left out in my first post hoping "common sense" would prevail, filling in the gaps.  I'll relent:<P>1) The argument of summoning a new pet for 400mana v/s healing your existing pet for 400mana.  <P>You know, that argument is quite a good one if you don't play a mage therefore having no clue about pets.  Could I get a show of hands by everybody who: keeps the first pet they summon, even if it's the weakest pet possible? (excluding epic of course)<P>Could I also get a show of hands by everybody who: does not burnout their pet.<P>Could I get one last show of hands by everybody who: does not damage shield their pet or give it daggers or rings or buffs/items of any kind.  This also includes making sure nobody in your group buffs your pets.<P>Now, those of you who raised your hands on those previous 3 scenerio's...yes!  <B>YOU ARE BEING RIPPED OFF BY THE NEW HEAL.</B>  But, I wouldn't worry too much about it, cause you are probably between levels 1-3 and are wondering when you will get pets.<P>Now, everybody who kept their hands down (except for the last point due to grouping), are you really going to let your lvl 45 pet who is burned out, wearing 2 lev rings, and has 2 daggers while simmering in a 33pt damage shield while beating the snot out of XXX mob die off just because you have a 1:10 chance in resummoning an equally powerful pet?  So you can recast burnout IV.  Recast DS, resummon daggers and rings, etc.  Hmmm how much mana does BO4 take?  How much mana does Cadeu take?  How long does it take to cast those?  And if you are having to chain-summon pets, how many times can you do all of this, v/s healing your existing pet?<P>Or, will you be happy that you now have a means of keeping your GOOD pet alive?  This is even applicable for epic pets - which no longer cast their DS immediately.<P><BR>2) Now, the thing about how groups should be looking for mages and not warriors because of our insane fast damage output.  This is true, and is still true, and will always be true.<P>Yes, we can outdamage any melee out there for the brief time our mana allows, if we can survive the aggro that comes with such insanity.  Even an epic rogue will have a hard time competing with a sirroco, followed by 3 fast scars, rinse and repeat - with pet also goin nuts.  That is, and has always been the attractiveness of Nukers.  It's not sustained damage over time, it's the <I>Kill the mob NOW!</I> type benefit we bring, ALONG with the very respectful sustained damage of our pet.  <P>Granted, against select mobs and places we find ourselves unable to do much other than summon rods and /moan, but those are thankfully not too common.  But, that is another entire topic.<P>Amneth, you obviously picked the wrong class to play if you demand to be the most damaging person in every group.  Quit now, and start a rogue, and hopefully you and I are not on the same server.  Either that, or start camping Crushbone as soon as you ding 60 so you can finally be top dog in the zone and wow the noobs.<P>It's not that I'm content with mages slipping further and further down the TopGun damage list - it's that there is nothing that will be done about it.  Sure, I could scream, whine and moan constantly about it, but then I would be just another punk kid, unhappy about everything unless I had the coolest look, and could brag about my uber power to the cute wood elf druid chick (even though she's really a 270lb 47yr old bald guy from Wyoming playing EQ in his mother's basement wearing nothin' but boxers and eating 3-day-old KFC.)<P>Just get over it - mages have never been the best damage dealer in the game.  We never will be, and it has never been the intent for us to be.<P>In fact, who the he11 was the bastage who started the whole "magicians are the best damage dealers in the game" rumor?  Somebody needs to hunt him down and make him recant his statement.<P>But I do like the idea of having a cold spell...oh that would be such a nice addition
