<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Anthe,<P>Couple of points.<P>First off, your insulting humor is lost on us level 1-3 noobs that disagree with you.  Argue your points.  If you don't agree with someone, tell us why and save the flames for your local blast furnace.<P>That said, if you really look at the spell data, some of what you argue doesn't hold water, at least not by the numbers in regards to chain summoning, vs. a 900 point, 400 mana heal (at level 60, btw, which exludes all of us level 1-3 noobs looking to wow people in Crushbone).  <P>My complaints with the post-50 mage has always been our dwindling ability to solo, something that was always possible for us to do (and a playstyle that was very enjoyable for me).  Yes, some people have complained that they want to be the big cheese in dealing damage; that's not my complaint.  Personally, I could care less if I was dead last in damage dealing, as long as my ability to solo was maintained throughout, and if there was some other caveat that made our class attractive to a group or raid (right now only CoH and our damage is that attractiveness with a few rare exceptions -- daggers of symbols for resists on a raid, fire pets for CoM, etc.).  In a group situation this spell would perform admirably if your pet actually drew some agro from a tank (doubtful unless your pet is the only real tank in the group).  But, lets really look at the facts of this spell.<P>Fact 1:  It's level 60.  How many mages (or anyone for that matter) are desperate for xp at level 60?  Does this help the level 60 mage?  Yeah, it will, but not much.  Most of a level 60's time is spent raiding, unless you're preoccupied farming something in some mid-level dungeon somewhere.<P>Fact 2:  The stats of this spell are as follows - 900 hit point heal for 400 mana.  Cast time is 7 seconds.  Spell recovery is 2.25 seconds with a 7.5 second recast.  So, that's about 17 seconds between heals.  Used between nukes this spell could tip a close fight in your favor, and keep your pet alive.  But, if you're in a tough fight, this spell may not keep your pet alive because of the lengthy time between heals.  <P>Is the option of having a heal rather than not having a heal, even if it's not till 60 worth it?  Yes.  Is it what the mage class has been looking for, to revive the renew summons series?  Well, I don't believe it is.<BR>I believe this would be a good spell to add at a much lower level, to keep that awesome 58-hitting earth pet you just made alive.  Again, I picture what these spells can do in a solo situation and how these new spells might help in that regard.  I mean, if I'm in a group why do I need to heal my pet anyway?  A cleric, druid or shammy can do it much more efficiently, while I use that 400 mana to land (assuming no resists) close to 2K of damage with Scirocco.  Killing a mob dead cold is, afterall, a better heal anyway  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>Personally, I think that chain-summoning an earth pet and throwing a DS on him might be more efficient than using this heal.  Even considering he's missing Burnout, your daggers, rings and whatever else you want to throw on him, you're still getting around 2K more hit points per 400 mana (admittedly 555 mana if you're counting cadeau of flame tossed in there -- but you're also medding while your earth pet does his job).  On a fast hitting mob, this method might be far more effective than using this heal.<P>Again, for me, it's all moot, as the spell is level 60.  If you're a level 60 with an epic pet, I can see this spell being used (the cast time on the epic pet is very long).  It will be interesting to see how this spell effects the level 60 mages out there.  Lower the spell level and make it slightly more efficient and I would call this heal a winner, hands down.<P>Oh yeah, your 1:10 chances of resummoning a level 45 pet are a little off, it's 1:5, or 2:10.  There is a 5 level range for our pets.<P>Longley Shadowsbane<BR>Level 55 mage (not 1-3 hehe), Saryrn<BR>-Retired- (hoping Luclin would change that)
</FONT>
